{
  "text": "It is easy to evaluate the right hand side, since the quantity S \u00b7 c 2 (X 6 ) is a familiar object that appears in the genus 1 topological A-model amplitude [CITATION_1] on X 6 , (6.11) Here, the sum runs over a basis of H 1,1 , with corresponding K\u00e4hler moduli t \u03b1 and Poincar\u00e9 dual divisors D \u03b1 . This topological string amplitude enters into a curvature squared term proportional to Re F 1 tr(R \u2212 R * ) 2 in the 4D low energy effective action. In the T 6 /Z 2 orientifold, as in type I or the heterotic string on T 6 , F 1 is determined by Green-Schwarz anomaly cancellation 10 to be F 1 \u221d \u03c4 dil + quantum corrections, (6.12) where \u03c4 dil = c (0) + i/g s . We will see in the next section that 1/g s of the T 6 /Z 2 orientifold maps to the K\u00e4hler modulus h of the Calabi-Yau X 6 , i.e., there is no s-dependence in the first term of Eq. (6.11) . Therefore, \u03c7(S) = S \u00b7 c 2 (X 6 ) = 0, and the fiber is an abelian surface.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "119331715"
